    "summary": "Solidarity (Solidarność) was a Polish independent trade union federation founded in August 1980 at the Lenin Shipyard in Gdańsk, following strikes that began in protest at government price increases. Led by electrician Lech Wałęsa and supported by the Catholic Church and Polish intellectuals, Solidarity quickly grew into the largest trade union in history, with a membership of approximately ten million workers — nearly a third of Poland's entire working-age population.\n\nSolidarity was more than a trade union. It functioned as a broad social movement challenging the legitimacy of communist rule, demanding free trade unions, freedom of the press, and the release of political prisoners. Its formation represented the first time in the Soviet bloc that workers had organized independently of state-controlled structures. The Polish government, under pressure from Moscow, imposed martial law in December 1981. Solidarity was declared illegal, thousands of its leaders were interned, and Wałęsa was imprisoned.\n\nThe suppression drove Solidarity underground but did not destroy it. Throughout the 1980s it continued operating clandestinely, supported by Western governments and the Catholic Church. The inefficiency of the communist economy and continuing social unrest eventually forced the government to negotiate. Round Table Agreements in early 1989 led to partially free elections in June 1989, which Solidarity won overwhelmingly. Poland became the first Eastern European country to transition peacefully from communism.\n\nSolidarity's success inspired and emboldened opposition movements across the Eastern Bloc and contributed directly to the wave of revolutions that swept Eastern Europe in 1989, including the [[event:2681|fall of the Berlin Wall]] and ultimately the [[event:2682|dissolution of the Soviet Union]].",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solidarity_(Polish_trade_union)",
